\section{Bifurcation Figures \& Comparative Metrics}
\label{sec:comparative_metrics}

To analyze the structural properties of the manifold across distinct microclimatic boundaries, the 4D solver pipeline was evaluated across three observational baseline regimes: CASES99 (flat open grassland), FLOSS (dense forest canopy), and SHEBA (perennial Arctic ice sheet).

The root mean square error (RMSE) of the local quadratic surface approximation provides a compact signature of phase-space localization induced by frictional damping and thermodynamic trapping.

These datasets are interpreted as parameter regimes of the same governing equations rather than distinct model forms. In this view, CASES99 and FLOSS primarily differ through boundary and surface-energy parameter values, which shift the effective geometry sampled by trajectories on and near the critical set. This provides a physical interpretation for comparatively brittle manifold excursions in CASES99 versus more buffered, rubbery localization behavior in FLOSS-like regimes.

